The problem faced here is regarding the (user_data_failure)
When Ec2 Boots ,you user_data tries  to execurte if any line fails it willskip that line 
and continue with the next line unless you use set -e 

To check which line failed Use: 
>> sudo cat /var/log/cloud-init-output.log
>> sudo cat /var/log/cloud-init.log

Look for lines with Error or failed - this will tell exactly which command didn't work 


Use this User_data instead if it doesn't work [Not checked ro used ] 
#!/bin/bash
# Update system
apt update -y
apt upgrade -y

# Install curl and Node.js 20 LTS
apt install -y curl
curl -fsSL https://deb.nodesource.com/setup_20.x | bash -
apt install -y nodejs

# Create application directory
mkdir -p /app

# Create a simple Node.js server
cat <<EOF > /app/server.js
const http = require('http');
const os = require('os');

const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
  res.writeHead(200, { "Content-Type": "text/plain" });
  res.end("Hello from instance: " + os.hostname());
});

server.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log("Server running on port 3000");
});
EOF

# Create systemd service to run Node.js server
cat <<EOF > /etc/systemd/system/nodeapp.service
[Unit]
Description=Node.js App
After=network.target

[Service]
ExecStart=/usr/bin/node /app/server.js
Restart=always
User=ubuntu
Environment=NODE_ENV=production
WorkingDirectory=/app

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
EOF

# Reload systemd and start service
systemctl daemon-reload
systemctl enable nodeapp
systemctl start nodeapp

# Optional: allow traffic on port 3000 via ufw (if firewall is active)
ufw allow 3000/tcp











